<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="151" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="151">
The name is an adjective derived from the species name of its closely similar sister species, 
<taxonomicName family="Tenthredinidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. aericeps" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="151" rank="species" species="aericeps">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">D. aericeps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Thomson, using the Latin diminutive suffix - 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="151">ellus</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
